# OpenClaw Trading System — Architectural Rules & Design Contract
# Version 1.0 | Author: Van Hellsing
# Scope: Governs all current containers (analyst, execution, heartbeat) and all future modules.
# This document is the single source of truth for system behavior, boundaries, and expansion standards.


════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
 SECTION I — CORE SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE (What the Bot MUST Do)
════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

[RULE-001] The Analyst Heartbeat Loop
  The analyst-brain container SHALL execute a regime evaluation cycle at a minimum frequency
  of once per 24 hours. The cycle interval MUST be controlled by the ANALYST_CYCLE_HOURS
  environment variable, injected at runtime. If the variable is absent at startup, the
  container MUST log a [FATAL] error and exit immediately — it must not silently default
  to any hardcoded value (see RULE-009). A hard-coded sleep_for(hours(24)) is not a valid
  implementation; the interval must be read from the environment so it can be tightened
  (e.g., to 1–4 hours during elevated volatility regimes) without requiring a code rebuild
  or container restart.

  On each cycle, the analyst must fetch two primary macro inputs: the SPY closing price
  relative to its 200-day Simple Moving Average (sourced from Alpaca Data API), and the
  current VIX level (sourced from Yahoo Finance). These two inputs feed directly into the
  RegimeStateMachine. If either data source fails, the cycle must be flagged as invalid —
  the machine must never evaluate on stale or partial data. Future data sources (options
  flow, yield curve, sector rotation) may be added as supplemental inputs but may NOT
  replace SPY/SMA and VIX as the primary regime triggers.
  
[RULE-002] Regime State Classification
  The RegimeStateMachine SHALL classify macro market conditions into exactly one of three
  operational states at all times:

    • RISK_ON     — VIX < 20 AND SPY price is above its 200-day SMA.
                    Full capital deployment. Kelly multiplier = 1.0.

    • TRANSITION  — VIX between 20–30 OR SPY is choppy around the SMA band.
                    Reduced deployment. Kelly multiplier = 0.5.

    • RISK_OFF    — VIX >= 30 OR SPY price is more than 2% below its 200-day SMA.
                    All new entries halted. Kelly multiplier = 0.0.

  The machine defaults to TRANSITION on startup until live data resolves a valid state.
  Future strategies (options, futures, sector ETFs) must read and respect the current regime
  state before sizing or routing any order.

[RULE-003] Payload Serialization & Internal Routing
  After each evaluation, the analyst SHALL serialize the full regime result into a validated
  JSON payload and transmit it via HTTP POST to the execution engine at:
  http://execution_engine:8080/webhook over the shared openclaw_net Docker bridge network.
  The payload must include: secret_key, ticker, action, price, risk_tier, vol, regime_state,
  atr, kelly_pct, and report_body. No field may be omitted. Future payload fields for new
  asset classes (options Greeks, futures basis, etc.) must be added as optional extension
  fields and must not break backward compatibility.

[RULE-004] The Execution Engine Server
  The execution-engine container SHALL maintain a persistent, multi-threaded HTTP listener on
  port 0.0.0.0:8080. Every incoming request must pass through three sequential gates before
  any logic executes:
    1. Schema Gate     — Payload is parsed strictly using nlohmann/json. Any malformed input
                         is rejected with HTTP 400 before memory allocation occurs.
    2. Auth Gate       — secret_key field must match the WEBHOOK_SECRET_TOKEN environment
                         variable. Any mismatch is silently dropped and logged as WARN.
    3. Logic Gate      — RSI momentum filter: BUY orders above RSI 70 are blocked (overbought).
                         SELL orders below RSI 30 are blocked (oversold).
  Only payloads that clear all three gates proceed to Kelly sizing and order routing.

[RULE-005] Position Sizing via the Kelly Calculator
  All position sizes SHALL be computed by the Kelly Calculator using the formula:
    K% = W - ((1 - W) / R)
  Where W = win rate and R = win/loss ratio, both injected at runtime via environment
  variables (KELLY_WIN_RATE, KELLY_WIN_LOSS_RATIO). The raw Kelly output is then scaled
  by a fixed Half-Kelly safety multiplier of 0.5 to reduce variance. Hard caps are enforced:
    • Maximum risk per trade: 10% of portfolio equity
    • Minimum risk per trade: 1% of portfolio equity (if strategy is active)

  Equity is fetched live from the Alpaca account before every order. On fetch failure, the
  engine MUST NOT proceed with any fallback or estimated equity value. It must instead:
    1. Attempt the equity fetch up to 3 times with exponential backoff: 2s → 4s → 8s
       (consistent with RULE-007).
    2. If all retries are exhausted, immediately halt all new order entries for the cycle.
    3. Log the failure as [CRITICAL] to container stdout.
    4. Fire a Telegram alert via the heartbeat monitor's notification channel (see RULE-006).
  A silent degradation fallback is not permitted — it masks a live infrastructure failure
  and directly violates the dual-channel observability mandate of RULE-013.
  Future asset classes (options contracts, futures lots) must implement their own sizing
  adapters but must call and respect the same Kelly percentage output — they may never
  override or bypass the 10% hard cap.
[RULE-006] The Heartbeat Monitor (Nox)
  The heartbeat-monitor container SHALL serve three persistent roles:
    1. SEC Radar       — Poll EDGAR every 30 seconds for new 8-K filings matching the
                         active watchlist. On match, route filing text through the Claude
                         AI risk analysis pipeline and push a structured alert to Telegram.
    2. Daily Scout     — At 11:30 AM ET each trading day, aggregate macro news headlines
                         (Alpaca News API) and targeted SEC filings into a Claude-generated
                         daily intelligence report, delivered to the Telegram channel.
    3. Conversational Agent — Maintain a persistent Telegram bot interface that allows
                         live queries against portfolio state, audit history, and system
                         status via the /status command or free-form text.
  All audit reports and trade history must be persisted to the SQLite memory bank at
  /app/data/memory_bank.db. The memory bank is the system's institutional knowledge base
  and must be mounted as a persistent Docker volume.


════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
 SECTION II — SAFETY & ARCHITECTURAL BOUNDARIES (What the Bot MUST NOT Do)
════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

[RULE-007] No Silent Cycle Failures (No Data Dropping)
  If the analyst fails to deliver its payload to the execution engine for any reason
  (container unreachable, network timeout, non-200 response), it MUST NOT silently skip
  the cycle and sleep for 24 hours. It must immediately enter an exponential-backoff retry
  loop: up to 5 attempts with delays of 2s → 4s → 8s → 16s → 32s. If all attempts are
  exhausted, the failure must be logged as CRITICAL and flagged for manual review. This rule
  applies to all future inter-container communication, not just the analyst-to-execution path.

[RULE-008] No Unguarded External Network Calls
  Every synchronous HTTP call to an external API (Alpaca, Telegram, Yahoo Finance, SEC EDGAR,
  Anthropic, or any future integration) MUST define explicit connection and read timeout
  thresholds at the point of client construction. Minimum enforced thresholds:
    • Connection timeout: 5 seconds
    • Read/response timeout: 10–15 seconds
  No network call may block indefinitely. This rule applies across all languages in the stack
  (C++ httplib, Python requests). Timeouts are not optional configuration — they are
  non-negotiable safety rails.

[RULE-009] No Hardcoded Secrets or Credentials
  No API keys, webhook tokens, bot tokens, secret keys, or any sensitive credential shall
  ever appear as a raw string literal in any source code file across any container. All such
  values must be injected at runtime via environment variables, loaded from a .env file that
  is explicitly listed in .gitignore and never committed to version control. If a required
  environment variable is missing at startup, the container must log a [FATAL] error and
  exit immediately rather than attempt to run in a degraded state. This rule applies to all
  future modules, scripts, and integrations added to this system.

[RULE-010] No Manual Payload Parsing
  No component in this system may parse incoming JSON payloads using manual string scanning,
  character offset indexing, substring splitting, or custom tokenization logic. All payload
  deserialization must use the designated native validation library for that container:
    • C++ containers  → nlohmann/json with structured exception handling
    • Python containers → the standard json module or pydantic for schema validation
  Malformed inputs must be rejected at the parser boundary before any field access or business
  logic executes. Parser exceptions must be caught at the handler level and return HTTP 400.


════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
 SECTION III — EXPANSION STANDARDS (Rules for Future Features)
════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

[RULE-011] Options & Futures Module Integration
  When options or futures trading modules are added, they must conform to the following:
    • Regime gate: Read current regime state before any order is sized or routed. RISK_OFF
      state must halt all new entries, including short-premium strategies.
    • Kelly adapter: Implement an asset-class-specific sizing adapter (e.g., contract multiplier
      normalization for futures, delta-adjusted notional for options) that outputs a Kelly
      percentage, which is then subject to the same 10% hard cap defined in RULE-005.
    • Payload contract: New signal fields (e.g., strike, expiry, delta, theta, IV_rank) must
      be added as optional, clearly named extension fields to the existing payload schema.
      They must not rename or repurpose existing required fields.

[RULE-012] New Container & Service Standards
  Any new service added to docker-compose.yml must:
    • Belong to the openclaw_net internal network for inter-service communication.
    • Define a restart: unless-stopped policy.
    • Inject all credentials exclusively through the environment block using .env references.
    • Include a clearly scoped responsibility comment in docker-compose.yml.
    • Follow the same three-gate validation model (schema, auth, logic) if it exposes any
      HTTP endpoint, whether internal or external.

[RULE-013] Observability & Auditability
  Every order executed, every regime state transition, and every SEC radar alert must produce
  a structured log entry (container stdout) AND a Telegram notification. Silent execution —
  where the system acts without a corresponding user-visible record — is not permitted.
  Future features must maintain this dual-channel observability standard. Structured log
  format: [LEVEL] [COMPONENT] Message. Acceptable levels: INFO, WARN, ERROR, FATAL, CRITICAL.

[RULE-014] Paper Trading First Policy
  All new trading strategies, asset class integrations, and execution modifications must be
  validated against the Alpaca Paper Trading environment before any live capital deployment.
  API base URLs must be managed via environment variables to allow clean promotion from paper
  to live without source code changes. No hardcoded live trading URLs are permitted.


════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
 SECTION IV — LIVE CAPITAL AI GUARDRAILS (Strict Mode)
════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

[RULE-015] No AI-Controlled Order Sizing or Execution
  Under no circumstances shall an LLM or generative AI model (Anthropic, OpenAI, or any
  future provider) directly determine trade size, order side, limit price, or execution
  routing. The AI layer's role is strictly limited to:
    • Text summarisation of SEC filings and macro news headlines.
    • Sentiment ranking and qualitative risk commentary.
    • Audit trail alerts delivered via Telegram.
  All quantitative execution boundaries — including but not limited to position sizing,
  price verification, momentum filters, and stop-loss placement — MUST be evaluated
  exclusively by compile-time, deterministic C++ mathematical algorithms inside the
  execution engine. An LLM output must never be used as a direct numeric input to an
  order payload without first passing through a validated, deterministic parsing and
  bounds-checking layer.

[RULE-016] AI Output Schema Verification & Fallbacks
  Any response returned by an external generative model that feeds into system state
  (e.g., the Claude 8-K risk analysis in process_automated_filing()) must be parsed
  against a strict, pre-defined schema before its values influence any downstream logic.
    • The model MUST be prompted to respond in a structured format. The current required
      format for SEC filing analysis is:
        RISK_FACTOR: [0.1–1.0] | SUMMARY: [one sentence]
      Future integrations must define and document their own schema in this Rules file
      before any code is written.
    • The parsing logic must catch all validation failures: truncated output, missing
      keys, out-of-range values, and non-numeric RISK_FACTOR strings.
    • If the parser fails to decode the AI output for any reason, the system MUST
      default to the most conservative safe state (e.g., RISK_FACTOR = 1.0 / High Risk)
      rather than crashing, logging silently, or using a partially parsed string.
    • A failed parse must be logged as [WARN] and reported to the Telegram channel so
      the operator is aware the AI response was unusable.

[RULE-017] External API Isolation & Rate-Limit Resiliency
  Failure of any AI-associated or notification service must never block or degrade the
  primary trading loops (the Analyst evaluation cycle or the Execution engine webhook).
    • All AI operations (Anthropic calls in heartbeat/monitor.py) must execute inside
      isolated, non-blocking daemon threads or microservices that are fully decoupled
      from the execution engine's request path.
    • Every thread or coroutine that interacts with an LLM API must enforce a dedicated
      timeout cap of 15 seconds — independent of the exchange API timeout defined in
      RULE-008 — to prevent a hung Anthropic call from stalling a Telegram notification
      loop or a scheduled task.
    • HTTP 429 (rate limit) responses from any AI provider must be caught explicitly,
      logged as [WARN], and handled with a linear back-off (e.g., 5 s → 10 s → 15 s)
      before the thread retries. They must never propagate as unhandled exceptions that
      terminate the calling thread (see also RULE-007 and the schedule_checker guard
      added in Patch C).
    • The Execution engine (C++) must have zero import or runtime dependency on any
      AI library. The boundary is enforced at the container level.

[RULE-018] Dynamic Sizing Hard Gate
  The Execution engine must enforce a two-condition physical gate on every calculated
  share quantity before an order payload is constructed or transmitted to Alpaca:

    Condition 1 — Zero-share block:
      If the Kelly calculator returns a share quantity of 0 (dollar allocation is smaller
      than the price of one share), the order MUST be aborted and logged as [CRITICAL].
      The engine is strictly prohibited from promoting a zero-share result to a minimum
      1-share purchase if that single share's value exceeds the 10 % maximum risk
      allowance for the current account equity.

    Condition 2 — Notional value ceiling:
      Before routing any order, the engine MUST verify:
        (Qty × CurrentPrice) ≤ (LiveAccountEquity × 0.10)
      If this condition is violated for any reason (e.g., a price spike between the
      sizing calculation and the order submission), the order must be instantly blocked
      and a [CRITICAL] alert fired to Telegram.

  Both conditions are non-negotiable and apply to all asset classes. No override flag,
  environment variable, or runtime parameter may disable either condition in production.